Remember to disinfect! Stay alert, stay alive!
I know these are crazy times, just do your part as an American to prevent this virus ü¶† from spreading! .
.

Here are some tips from the #CDC

Clean and disinfect
Clean AND disinfect frequently touched surfaces daily. This includes tables, doorknobs, light switches, countertops, handles, desks, phones, keyboards, toilets, faucets, and sinks.
If surfaces are dirty, clean them: Use detergent or soap and water prior to disinfection.
To disinfect:
Most common EPA-registered household disinfectants will work. Use disinfectants appropriate for the surface.

Options include:

Diluting your household bleach.
To make a bleach solution, mix:
5 tablespoons (1/3rd cup) bleach per gallon of water
OR
4 teaspoons bleach per quart of water
Follow manufacturer‚Äôs instructions for application and proper ventilation. Check to ensure the product is not past its expiration date. Never mix household bleach with ammonia or any other cleanser. Unexpired household bleach will be effective against coronaviruses when properly diluted.

Alcohol solutions.
Ensure solution has at least 70% alcohol.
Other common EPA-registered household disinfectants. .

insta_description: |Reno Police, NV, USA| üá∫üá∏ Established in 1864, the Reno area (then called Lake's Crossing) did not have an established police department. If a crime occurred, the few residents handled it at the time. Mr. Myron C. Lake, who developed the small community, sold 80 acres of land to the Central Pacific Railroad (CPRR) in 1868. Once CPRR built the railroad station, the Construction Superintendent Charles Crocker decided to name the community after Major General Jesse Lee Reno, a Union Officer killed in the American Civil War. Land lots were auctioned and within two weeks, 100 houses had been built. West Street bound the city limits on the west, Truckee River on the south, East Street on the east, and 4th Street on the north. With the influx of people to the area due to mining, farming, and the railroad, the crime rate increased. Most of the criminal activity was dealt with by the residents of Reno. At the time, the only sheriff in the area was in the Carson City region. RPD was formally established in 1903 to serve the growing community of Reno, which at that time consisted of a couple of square miles and had a population of around 1000. Since then, RPD has grown along with the rest of the city. As of 2013, RPD provided law enforcement services to an area of 105.9 square miles and a population of approximately 233,294 citizens. insta_description: ‚Ä¢ gold ‚Ä¢ It was as if I were holding a bag of gold in my hands. I handed it to the woman behind the counter; dressed in worry & glove protected hands. she carefully examined it and proceeded to toss it from hand to hand. She looked at my mother and then at me, and asked in complete disbelief, ‚ÄúWhere did you find this?‚Äù I told her I had stumbled upon an abandoned cart in a deserted corner of the store. The cart had other items but this was the only thing my eyes could see, as this was store #3 that lacked in essentials. She proceeded to say that we were lucky to find it as she slowly rested it on the counter. The realization of what was happening seemed surreal, a scene only plausible in film - so I grabbed it, placed it gently in its own reusable bag, and headed home. It was a quick drive back, even with the storm approaching. I found myself relinquishing my saddened thoughts of wanting to help those more fragile than me, for even I hopelessly roamed the eery aisles that were abundant in color only one week ago. After all, there are those who are simply looking to check off their weekly grocery list; toilet paper, disinfecting wipes, eggs, and that precious loaf of golden bread ‚Ä¢ üçû ‚Ä¢

accessibility_caption: Photo by Elizabeth Ihidoy in San Francisco, California. Image may contain: food
insta_description:
Did you go panic shopping and buy more winter citrus than you‚Äôll be able to use? If you get to a point where you think your oranges/mandarins/etc. are ready for the compost bin, they probably are not. Unless they‚Äôre moldy, you can make use of them! 
Last night I realized I had an entire drawer of tired mixed citrus that had been sitting for a long while, so I decided to clear it out. I used a microplane to zest navel oranges, blood oranges and mandarins. I left the zest out on a parchment-lined baking tray and this morning it‚Äôs almost dry. One more day and I‚Äôll have perfect dried citrus zest for a billion kitchen projects that is WAY tastier than store bought! 
I squeezed the juice out of all the fruit and froze it into a silicon tray. Those popular baby food molds/the ones people use for Instant Pot or sous vide egg bites each hold about 2 ounces or 1/4 cup of liquid‚Äîperfect for portioning out juice to thaw for later use.

Though our food supply chain hasn‚Äôt yet been interrupted, the experience of empty shelves and panicked shoppers should serve as an enormous wake up call. There is no point to waste food when you can make good use of it with only a few minutes of work. Learn lessons, folks, and support your local restaurants, growers, and grocers if they are open!

Healing Food Mandala by international artist Rolandas Dabrukas www.WhimsicalFineArts.com or www.RolandasArt.com Eat more fruits, berries and vegetables and be healthy and happy. Love oranges and lemons. Oranges are a type of low calorie, highly nutritious citrus fruit. As part of a healthful and varied diet, oranges contribute to strong, clear skin and can help lower a person‚Äôs risk of many conditions.

Oranges are popular due to their natural sweetness, the many different types available, and the diversity of uses. For example, a person can consume them in juices and marmalades, eat them whole, or use zested peel to add a tangy flavor to cakes and desserts.

This popular citrus fruit is particularly known for its vitamin C content. However, oranges contain a range of other plant compounds and antioxidants that may reduce inflammation and work against disease. As an excellent source of the antioxidant vitamin C, oranges may help combat the formation of free radicals that cause cancer.  Love lemons too. Lemons are a popular fruit that people use in small quantities to add flavor to food. However, they rarely consume them alone due to their intense, sour taste.

Lemons give flavor to baked goods, sauces, salad dressings, marinades, drinks, and desserts, and they are also a good source of vitamin C.

One 58 gram (g) lemon can provide over 30 milligrams (mg) of vitamin C.

Vitamin C is essential for health, and a deficiency can lead to health problems. accessibility_caption: Photo by Lorri Lee Lown in Double Peak with @mermaidseries, @guenergylabs, @pactimo_official, @thesisbike, and @ridgesupplyarsenal. Image may contain: sky, tree, outdoor and nature
insta_description:
Two weeks ago, we were scheduled to fly to Italy and Denmark to visit family.  We chose not to go due to uncertainty surrounding COVID-19.  Instead, we chose to spend a few days relaxing in Southern California, running on the beach, riding bikes, and camping in the desert. When I shot this photo, after climbing Double Peak, I had no idea what the next two weeks would hold for us.
üö≤
It‚Äôs not business as usual in Northern California and I think that might be a good thing.  Today we started a 21-day mandatory Shelter-in-Place.  The goal is to slow down the spread of COVID-19 and not overwhelm the medical system.
üö≤
Yesterday, I was filled with stress, mostly about the unknown.  I shut down my business. I was grieving the life I knew, which will inevitably change in the future.  Today, I‚Äôm relaxed and energized and ready to make the most of this opportunity to reset and move forward.
üö≤
Have you ever thought ‚Äúwhat if I could change this?‚Äù but you felt it was impossible.  What if we really can start from scratch, draw a line in the sand, and change our lives?  And can we do this on the broader scale of our entire society?  What are the things we would change?  Will we see greater acceptance of remote work (and a correlated reduction in emissions, traffic, and stress)? Will we see a change in how we all prepare for an emergency all the time, not just when it hits?  Will we identify supply chain weaknesses?  Will we become kinder, more thoughtful humans?
üö≤
Of course, there will be negative impacts, too.  People are living in fear.  They‚Äôre hoarding water and toilet paper and buying guns.  Hourly employees and small business owners, who don‚Äôt have guaranteed income, will suffer badly, and they may not recover.  We will lose lives and others will suffer long-term medical implications.
üö≤
Today I challenge you to think about what YOU can do to turn this experience into a positive one.  Tell me how you can make a difference in this brave new world.
.
.
.
.
.

Image may contain: tree, plant, outdoor, nature and water
insta_description:
Walking San Francisco & Thinking Out Loud

From: https://www.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=22257

A mixture of trees and shrubs creates a multi-layered canopy that supports the growth of each species in the redwood grove. Diversity is crucial to the redwood forest; every plant, tree, and even fallen logs, play a crucial role. The following trees and plants are commonly found in a redwood forest and each plays its part in the ecosystem. . 
DOUGLAS FIR
A prominent member of the redwood forest, this tree is second in size only to the coast redwood. It is easily differentiated from a redwood by its dark gray bark and 3/4" cones. 
BIG LEAF MAPLE
This tree thrives in moist coastal climates. Its three to five lobed leaves turn bright yellow and orange in the fall. 
CALIFORNIA BAY LAUREL
The leathery dark green leaves of this tree produce a pungent odor when crushed. The Pomo Indians used parts of this tree for food and medicine. 
TAN OAK
This evergreen, which is not a true oak, has smooth gray bark and glossy toothed leaves ending in sharp spines. Traditionally, the acorns were used for food and medicine. Tannic acid is derived from the bark of these trees and used to tan leather. 
CALIFORNIA HAZEL
This shrub grows 3-10 feet tall and produces edible nuts. Native Indians used the stems of this shrub to make baskets.

WOODROSE
This is a small shrub that produces dainty pink blossoms in the spring, that are replaced by bright rose hips in the autumn. 
REDWOOD TRILLIUM
This flower is a member of the lily family and thrives in the cooler climate of the redwoods. A three-petaled white flower blooms in the spring.

REDWOOD SORREL
This plant forms a beautiful green carpet on the shady forest floor, folding its leaves when needed to preserve moisture. In the spring it produces a delicate three-petaled violet flower.

SWORD FERN
This fern is a striking plant with individual fronds that arise from a single base and can grow up to five feet long.

BRACKEN FERN
It has a main stem can grow 1-4 feet¬†with lateral branches. Native Americans used the roots¬†to make baskets.

Image may contain: bicycle, sky, bridge and outdoor
insta_description:
Walking San Francisco & Thinking Out Loud

The photographer in me says to crop out the porta potties but the tour guide knows what a welcome sight they as you enter Fort Baker after riding the Golden Gate Bridge. The Bosch e-bike was my ride today. The shock absorbers were a little tight (JK) but the bike handled really well and the electric power boost was just as Paige described today when she waited on me. "It has that extra kick you want when you need it". There are times you need to step on it and pass by gawkers and going 10 mph up a steep hill makes a huge difference in what hills you want to go up and how much more you get to see. This quote caught my attention on the Bosch e-bike website:

Uphill Flow

By the Uphill Flow we shift our borders, look for new ways, and overcome an unsuspected challenge. We master the seemingly impossible.

Thanks for the likes, follows and comments!üôèüôè

accessibility_caption: Photo by #WalkSanFrancisco in Conzelman Road with @cntraveler, @frommers, @condenasttraveller, @airbnbexperiences, @toursbylocals, @bayarea_buzz, @walksanfrancisco, and @visitsausalito. Image may contain: one or more people, people standing and outdoor
insta_description:
Walking San Francisco & Thinking Out Loud

I should repeat that I did an e-bike tour with the nicest family from Lisbon, Portugal. In this photo we are about 1/3 of the way up Hawk Hill at which time I was seeing more fog than expected so I decided to do a photo shoot at the overlook. I really luv this picture starting with Sarah & Anne (l to r) who were both smiling with eyes open. In the background you can make out the bottom of the South Tower of the Golden Gate Bridge. Finally and PURE- LUCKILY I somehow captured, out of the foggy sky, a Mission Blue Butterfly that is on the endangered species list and it somehow appeared flying by with wings up and markings visible in this photo. In my book that means good luck and safe travels to my new friends from Lisbon, Portugal even if it turns out to be a viceroy or monarch, it's still lucky.
Anne's, who owns a restaurant that caters to tourists and locals in Lisbon, had on a sweatshirt that said LEAD WITH LOVE. I wasn't sure if this was a political statement or if she was trying to send me a message & wanted me to not power-up and go really fast up to the top of HAWK HILL. 
Thanks for the likes, follows and comments!üôèüôè

Yesterday was crazy...
-In the morning, the school announced all students had 3 days to get all belongings out of all studios before campus closes.
-Just afternoon the county issued a ‚ÄúShelter in Place‚Äù for all of the Bay Area and the school announces ‚Äúwe close at 5pm.‚Äù
-At 2 I received orders to bail and shut off the furnace. -Thanks to @c.mura and @jon_ryan_moreno we ladled 900 lbs of Glass and scraped the liner in less than 3 hours.
-By 5pm all of @cacollegeofarts Studios were Closed and Locked
-About 20 minutes after getting home... @simplicj and I heard a loud crash, that sounded like it was in our kitchen. There was a car accident on our corner and one of the cars was on Fire. I quickly grabbed my Fire Extinguisher and put out the flames, before any First Responders arrived.
-Did I mention yesterday was crazy and that was just Monday?
-Now I get to spend the next 10 days, while under ‚ÄúShelter,‚Äù babysitting the Furnace while it ramps down.
-Stay safe out there, things are getting crazy!

insta_description:
Glossy Ibis (Plegadis falcinellus)
This long and sexy beast can be found in shallow lakes and marshes from west India to southern California. Appearing almost black at first, the glossy Ibis, turns a deep bronzy/green/violet color when the sun hits it just right. Like egrets, the Glossy Ibis picks through the mud to stir up minnows and water beetles, and can be seen preening its feathers with a long curved bill. They tend to nest together as a group, then venture off on their own, which has made them the most widespread of the ibis species.

accessibility_caption: Photo by Alexa Rowe on March 17, 2020. Image may contain: sky, tree, cloud, outdoor and nature
insta_description: Trying to find joy in this whole quarantine thing. Note this comes from a TOTAL place of privilege (I have a flexible job and am in a very low risk category) but I‚Äôve been trying to get the most out of a ‚Äúfrustrating‚Äù situation. The streets of LA are so clear right now that it is wildly fun to roam. Last night I went running and dancing in them without a car in sight. The air is better than it‚Äôs been in months (far less pollution and it smells amazing from rain). My body‚Äôs pent up adrenaline has been freed (since groundlings / all film industry stuff is on pause) so my insanely busy life has taken a moment to stop and I feel I can breathe again. Finding beauty in being STILL. I feel no guilt not working towards anything (which I feel I always am). I feel free and childish. I feel imaginative and creative. I feel wild. It is an amazing feeling: to slow and be still. We rarely get the excuse to do it. Practice social distancing but take this also as a moment of stillness and meditation. We don‚Äôt often get completely off the hook for just ‚Äúbeing‚Äù instead of ‚Äúdoing‚Äù. So for those of us who can, try and enjoy it. And look for ways to help your local elders / those at risk! Find joy in this stillness. And think of all of the massive reductions in emissions this is causing. That being said if you‚Äôve been helping your community in any way, please let me know!! Looking for ways to do the same ‚òÄÔ∏è #tuesdaythoughts #quarantine #losangeles #california #socialdistancing

insta_description:
Guys No Advil, No Ibuprofen for now!! According to Olivier Veran, the Minister of Solidarity and Health, a common medication that can be bought over the counter has been found to worsen your condition if you happen to have an unconfirmed case of COVID-19. These drugs are Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) and go by the names of Advil, Ibuprofen, and aspirin. These medications are usually bought to treat common colds, and flu's as they reduce fevers, pain and can even prevent blood clots. The situation we are in as a country is wild.  Every day things are changing left and right.  For those who prioritize fitness and health, it‚Äôs been even more challenging with gyms now closing.  San Diego just pulled the trigger on that yesterday.

Luckily Self Made Training Facility isn‚Äôt a ‚Äúgym‚Äù and we are open and ready to rock.  It‚Äôs a private facility that isn‚Äôt open to the public, and with almost 10,000 square feet there is more than enough room to follow the social distancing rules of 6 feet between individuals.

2020 Mazda CX-5 .

The name ‚ÄúMazda‚Äù was introduced to Japan in October 1931. Mazda started its life as a cork manufacturer back in 1920. The year 1931 was when Mazda, then called the Toyo Kogyo Co., Ltd., launched the ‚ÄúMazda-go‚Äù, a tricycle truck which is a first vehicle coming out of the company. The naming of the tricycle was considered by Jujiro Matsuda, the second president and substantial founder of Toyo Kogyo, and other key members.
.
Made by a company that was then managed by a man named Matsuda, the name ‚ÄúMazda-go‚Äù sounds fitting enough. The question is, how come it was spelt ‚ÄúMazda‚Äù instead of ‚ÄúMatsuda‚Äù? ‚ÄúMazda‚Äù comes from Ahura Mazda, the god of harmony, intelligence and wisdom from the earliest civilization in West Asia. Key members of Toyo Kogyo interpreted Mazda as a symbol of the beginning of the East and the West civilization, but also a symbol of the automotive civilization and culture. Striving to make a contribution to the world peace and to be a light in the automotive industry, Toyo Kogyo was renamed Mazda Motor Corporation. ‚ÄúMazda‚Äù was also a perfect way to pay respect to the substantial founder, whose family name is pronounced very close to ‚ÄúMazda‚Äù .
(Source: @mazdausa )

accessibility_caption: Photo by @circleofblue in Foster City, California. Image may contain: ocean, sky, bicycle, outdoor, nature and water
insta_description:
Six miles of mounded rock and earth already partially encircle this Bay Area city some 20 miles south of San Francisco. The levees protect about 17,000 parcels of land here and in neighboring San Mateo from waves, tides, and flood waters.

Those earthen embankments, however, are not protective enough. Not for floods today and not for floods of the future.

Spurred by a recent change in federal flood zone maps and a desire to prepare for rising seas, Foster City is in the process of raising its levees by 1 to 7 feet. Residents voted in 2018 to tax themselves in order to pay for the estimated $90 million upgrade. Learn more about how rising seas and a better understanding of flood risks prompt shoreline communities to build higher levees through the link in our bio. 
The multi-use Bay Trail extends along the levee that protects Foster City, California from flooding. Photo ¬© Brett Walton/Circle of Blue

insta_description:
Dear mama dreading the future for your kids...be the steward‚ú®

They say a person needs three things in life to be happy...
1. Something to love
2. Something to do
3. Something to hope for

Close your eyes. Visualize your answer to these three things. If you are a mother, your answers revolve around your children.

There is a global outpouring of hope, love and humanity in light of the health crisis upon us.  How can we be a steward of hope for our kids?

Stewardship is conducting, supervising or managing something. Especially the careful and responsible management of something entrusted to one‚Äôs care.

To those of us with children, a beautiful reminder to be the light our babes need. Watch the press conferences in another room if you can, so you can keep your composure while we process the information our local, state and federal governments offer. At only 8 mos old, my son can sense my panic and overwhelm. But I can do better. I can protect him from my confusion by remembering one simple thing. To be a good steward of his experience to the best of my ability. I‚Äôm focusing on play, hugs, laughter and smiles because that is what he is used to. It‚Äôs day by day for us all and by no means do I suggest downplaying this crisis. But remember, our little ones need us to be strong. To be a good role model. To be a good steward ü§ç Sending light and love mamas! #motherhoodinspired #motherhoodinsquares #stewardship #light #love #zenmomlife #losangeles #california #coronaviruslosangeles

Is your Solar Plexus Chakra blocked?
The Manipura (Solar Plexus chakra) is our source of personal power, self-confidence and sense of purpose. This chakra is located around your navel area of the body near your upper abdomen and breastbone. Due to its location, it is also connected with the digestive system. 
If there is an imbalanced Solar Plexus chakra you may experience a problem with self-esteem and self-image. 
Imbalances of the Solar Plexus may also manifest in the physical body such as fatigue, overeating, excessive weight around the stomach, and digestive system disorders such as IBS, ulcers, hypoglycemia, and diabetes.

How to heal your Solar Plexus Chakra:
- Set an intention like described above.
- Use essential oils. Choose any of the essential oils or a blend of them. Add 5 drops of oil to a tsp of carrier oil like jojoba or almond oil. Put the oil mixture in your hands and rub them together. Deeply inhale the scent then place your hands over your Solar Plexus challenge and allow the energy of the oils infuse your chakra or rub the oil directly on your skin.
- Meditate with a crystal of your choice while holding it on your left hand.
- Chant: "RA" for few minutes
- Try Reiki and/or yoga.
